lines.value: it is believed that the turkic peoples are natives of central asia
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: some historians claim that the turkic peoples originated in western asia and migrated in prehistoric times to central asia while others believe that migration to western asia and interactions in various parts of the world by turkic peoples in ancient times before the advent of the huns occurred via central asia
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: some also claim that comparisons to the ancient sumerian language which some label as ural altaic to modern turkic languages show common vocabulary
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: based on these comparisons is then the claim that the sumerians are the most ancient documented turkic people that they originated from east of the caspian sea but established a civilization in mesopotamia
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: others dismiss this as an expression of pan turkist ideology pointing out that most linguists consider sumerian a language isolate
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: further the classification of languages into an ural altaic group is often criticised due to perceived lack of evidence and perceived lack of obvious similarties between languages classified as such
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: some scholars will also consider the huns whose origins go back to 1200 bce as one of the earlier turkic tribes
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: leaving these controversies aside the precise date of the initial expansion from the early homeland remains unknown
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the first state known as turk giving its name to the many states and people afterwards was that of the gokturks gog = blue or celestial in the 6th century ad.later turkic peoples include the karluks mainly 8th century uighurs kirghiz oghuz or guz turks and turkmens
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: as these peoples were founding states in the area between mongolia and transoxiana they came into contact with the muslim people and gradually adopted islam
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: however there were also and still are turkic people belonging to different religions including christians jews see khazars buddhists and zoroastrians
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: turkic soldiers in the army of the abbasid caliphs emerged as de facto rulers of most of the muslim middle east except syria and egypt particularly after the 10th century
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: oghuz and other tribes captured and dominated various countries under the leadership of the seljuk dynasty and eventually captured the territories of the abbasid dynasty and the byzantine empire
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: meanwhile kirghiz and uighurs were struggling with each other and with the mighty chinese empire
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: kirghiz people finally settled in the region that is now referred to as kyrgyzstan
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: tatar peoples conquered volga bulgars in what is today southern russia following the westward sweep of the mongols under genghis khan in the 13th century
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: bulgars was named tatars by russians mistakenly
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: native tatars lives only in asia european tatars are in fact bulgars
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: bulgars came to europe in 7-8th century
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: everywhere turkic groups mixed to some extent with other local populations
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: as the seljuks declined after the mongol invasion the ottoman empire emerged as a new important turkic state which came to dominate not only the middle east but also southeastern europe and parts of southwestern russia and northern africa
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: meanwhile other turkic groups founded dynasties in iran like the safavids and northern india the mughal empire
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the ottoman empire grew weaker in the face of repeated wars with russia and austria and the emergence of nationalist movements in the balkans and finally gave way after world war i to the present day republic of turkey
lines.name: Tatar
